  <span id="freeText4376225307502294143" style="display:none">I couldn't read this fast enough. It has been my second read from Christopher Paul Curtis and I ate up the story like a kid eating a sucker behind the couch his mom told him not to eat in the first place. <br /><br />It was funny and serious with racial issues thrown out to the reader. <br /><br />Told in the narrative of Kenneth Watson, it follows his family and life in school focusing on his bully brother Byron (By). Each chapter is hilariously recounted as only a kid in third grade can remember the events or understanding of the events. <br /><br />The family finally travels from Flint, Michigan to Birmingham, Alabama where in 1963 they learn a scary lesson about hatefulness. <br /><br />I grew fond of Kenny and his family esp his parents. Would recommend this to YA readers to learn something on history; things history books don't teach. <br /><br />Will be reading more of Curtis. 2 thumbs and toes up. Lol</span>
